At Title 6 we enter upon the discussion of the last department os Private Law-the ius quod ad actiones pertinet. The division oi law into law ol Persons and law of Things is perhaps as old as Cicero (lavent. i. 24), and apparently was the basis ol aclassiiication in the Perpetual Edict (Dig. i. 5. a) ; but Gaius, so lar as we know, was the first jurist who added the third division os actiones. It may be doubted whether his own conception ol this branch ol his system was as clear as a more modern writer might have made it. The term actio, as is shown in the note on Tit. 6. pr., has a variety ol meanings in the writings of the Roman lawyers, and two oi them seem to be more or less blended in Gaius’ fourth Book, which wholly relates to this topic. Inone sense, actio is a right of action; and a treatise upon rights of action would correspond with what writers on analy- tical Jurisprudence term the Law of Sanctioning or Remedial rights.
